FQIKbfagHuZRsIgL_kg8N_tvjv5S6U6uTmnkIppNP4tXXZ8xorPxlmMYbyYpJBwk=\",\"summary\":[{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Analyzing code tracking and build issues**\\n\\nI'm observing that a file was recently tracked, which might be due to previous changes being staged. I'm focused on ensuring final field writes are handled correctly in the native environment. It seems the build.gradle's add-opens exposes java.lang, which could complicate tests related to defining classes. I need to consider the order of definitions in tests to avoid class name duplication and ensure checkstyle is compliant, especially around static initializations and metadata concerns.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Exploring reflection in tests**\\n\\nI see that the test's direct reflection call to `ReflectUtils.class.getDeclaredField` interacts with dynamic access, but the active class report only shows library call sites. This could be an issue since the metadata might include ReflectUtils fields, depending on conditions. The user-code filter treats certain libraries as user code, complicating things. If the test reflects on a library class, it might not be recorded. I could consider adding extra test metadata for reflection, especially for public methods that need access during native image compilation.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering native image compilation**\\n\\nI'm thinking about running a native image compile without a prior agent. The TCK plugin likely generates the necessary metadata, and it seems the existing pattern is working. I need to check if my build.gradle requires add-opens for `jdk.unsupported/sun.misc`. Accessing `sun.misc.Unsafe.theUnsafe` requires `setAccessible`, so I should confirm whether the module `jdk.unsupported` exports or opens `sun.misc`. Since existing tests are using it, I’m optimistic this setup should be okay!\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_ezriEKTvW2T78V5j4gTOfvkN|fc_00e5e720f1c4bb700169f68ea7fb60819d986aeb3221f045